38
00:09:26.030 --> 00:09:28.300
Greg: is,

39
00:09:30.450 --> 00:09:42.109
Greg: One notion there was to get the validation code out of the clients to go ahead and put it on the blockchain.

40
00:09:42.120 --> 00:09:54.949
Greg: I noticed Vitalik has suggested putting the identity pre-compiled on the blockchain, and researchers have suggested that for other

41
00:09:54.970 --> 00:10:12.260
Greg: for other things that are currently pre-compiles. And the notion is, if we get it on the blockchain, we only need to get it right once. Then it makes client jobs really easy. If a contract

42
00:10:12.430 --> 00:10:27.170
Greg: has a magic header, then the header will point at the address of the validation code. It's not any harder than running the init code, and if it doesn't pass validation, then it

43
00:10:27.530 --> 00:10:30.059
Greg: Then it fails and doesn't get run.

44
00:10:30.350 --> 00:10:36.430
Greg: So this is… This is an answer to…

45
00:10:36.550 --> 00:10:42.070
Greg: To Marius's continuous… continuing concern about technical debt.

46
00:10:42.220 --> 00:10:52.700
Greg: To try and get it down to… all the clients need to do is to add a return stack, and the… the opcodes amount to,

47
00:10:53.360 --> 00:11:03.220
Greg: a little bit of instruction, decoding, push the return, push the return address and to return, pop the return address.

48
00:11:03.540 --> 00:11:04.490
Greg: Oh.

49
00:11:04.760 --> 00:11:05.840
Greg: So…

50
00:11:06.020 --> 00:11:21.720
Greg: Try and make it as simple as possible and if it turns out nobody in the world ever uses this, we're carrying on a very tiny amount of debt and it will get used.

51
00:11:22.010 --> 00:11:30.269
Greg: and I don't have a whole lot to say about it until

52
00:11:30.370 --> 00:11:37.189
Greg: I know what what it is people want to do, what questions they have, what comments.

53
00:11:37.550 --> 00:11:42.900
Greg: and just speak. I'm not gonna deal with with people's hands being up.

54
00:11:44.560 --> 00:11:47.119
Ben Adams: Okay, so.

55
00:11:48.740 --> 00:11:55.200
Ben Adams: As I understand it, only… These opcodes will only be valid.

56
00:11:55.430 --> 00:12:04.089
Ben Adams: Inside, A contract that starts with the magic header and to deploy that.

57
00:12:04.780 --> 00:12:10.780
Ben Adams: If your contract starts with the magic header, it will be validated at create time.

58
00:12:11.170 --> 00:12:15.630
Ben Adams: And then, after that, It's sort of like your life.

59
00:12:18.070 --> 00:12:21.960
Greg: The opcodes are valid whether or not.

60
00:12:22.310 --> 00:12:29.169
Greg: They're in magic code. The opcodes are simply being added, so they're backwards compatible.

61
00:12:29.530 --> 00:12:37.690
Greg: If they're in, if they're in code that's labeled, that's valid, that's magic.

62
00:12:38.360 --> 00:12:48.420
Greg: then they have to obey the rules. But if they're not in Magic Cove, they don't have to obey the rules. But they're still there and can be used.

63
00:12:48.840 --> 00:12:49.930
Greg: Oh.

64
00:12:53.200 --> 00:13:12.420
Greg: And this is important that this is genuine backwards compatibility. It's not hand waving that just says, well, yeah, we've we've got a tag here. So it's it's really a different interpreter. So it's it's backwards compatible in that sense. And I don't think that's

65
00:13:12.530 --> 00:13:13.990
Greg: I don't think that's…

66
00:13:14.660 --> 00:13:23.459
Greg: the level of compatibility we want. We want the interpreter itself not to care whether it's validated.

67
00:13:23.980 --> 00:13:24.890
Greg: So…

68
00:13:25.470 --> 00:13:28.460
lightclient: What's the point of the validation?

69
00:13:29.610 --> 00:13:30.740
Greg: Umm.

70
00:13:32.460 --> 00:13:34.300
Greg: Basically…

71
00:13:34.940 --> 00:13:51.079
Greg: A client can check it. Luke's not here, but he was trying to actually write a compiler for his client and discovered he just could not do it.

72
00:13:51.300 --> 00:14:08.489
Greg: Could not do it efficiently. Could not optimize what he had. So it will affect clients that are trying to optimize the code. That was my initial motivation. I set out to

73
00:14:08.980 --> 00:14:16.869
Greg: to do what I'd done for a JVM at Oracle, which was simply make one pass over the

74
00:14:16.880 --> 00:14:30.560
Greg: one pass over the byte code and translate it to register code, which would make it run faster, and then one pass over the register code and convert it to machine code. And it turned out to be

75
00:14:30.660 --> 00:14:31.840
Greg: Impossible.

76
00:14:32.120 --> 00:14:33.100
Greg: Yeah.

77
00:14:33.260 --> 00:14:35.450
Greg: And it was… oh!

78
00:14:35.610 --> 00:14:53.460
Greg: put in these 2 instructions and arrange that the instructions be used properly, and it becomes possible, just like it is for the Jvm. Just like it is for Wasm, just like it is for cli, and I'm scratching my head and going.

79
00:14:53.690 --> 00:14:56.290
Greg: You know. Why?

80
00:14:57.820 --> 00:15:17.280
Greg: And it's too late to fix legacy code, but at least we can have a marker that says at least this code, you know that you can traverse it in one pass and therefore you can do all kinds of nice things.

81
00:15:17.460 --> 00:15:18.510
Greg: Oh.

82
00:15:18.810 --> 00:15:21.200
lightclient: I guess I'm just trying to understand, like, how…

83
00:15:21.590 --> 00:15:33.310
lightclient: required it is to do the validation in the protocol with the introduction of these opcodes, because I think most clients won't implement these optimizations from the get-go.

84
00:15:34.270 --> 00:15:39.490
lightclient: And the validation is probably the most contentious point of this, these proposals.

85
00:15:41.110 --> 00:15:46.730
Greg: Well, not having it was a contentious point in 2315.

86
00:15:46.880 --> 00:15:52.329
Greg: Some devs specifically objected that it wasn't there.

87
00:15:52.860 --> 00:15:53.840
Greg: Yeah.

88
00:15:54.090 --> 00:15:56.499
Greg: and then for EOF.

89
00:15:56.660 --> 00:16:10.729
Greg: The other devs objected that the code would only run in EOF, so EOF essentially marked a whole new interpreter.

90
00:16:10.910 --> 00:16:21.579
Greg: And I don't know that all clients will want to take advantage of this right away. They're going to need to wait for compilers to catch up.

91
00:16:21.710 --> 00:16:30.160
Greg: you know, you know, it's… it's not gonna be possible to get everything to land all at once.

92
00:16:30.330 --> 00:16:31.430
Greg: Yeah,

93
00:16:32.630 --> 00:16:33.180
Ben Adams: So, yeah.

94
00:16:33.390 --> 00:16:41.020
Ben Adams: So… As I understand it, the magic header guarantees that the code is well behaved.

95
00:16:41.820 --> 00:16:43.890
Ben Adams: But you can use the up codes.

96
00:16:44.860 --> 00:16:50.999
Ben Adams: Without the header, but it doesn't necessarily, it's not necessarily well structured.

97
00:16:51.590 --> 00:16:54.390
Ben Adams: Right. So if you put the magic pedal, you deploy it.

98
00:16:54.930 --> 00:16:57.439
Ben Adams: You… you guarantee at deployment time.

99
00:16:57.970 --> 00:17:01.150
Ben Adams: It's valid. Never have to check it again.

100
00:17:01.700 --> 00:17:02.430
Greg: Right.

101
00:17:04.380 --> 00:17:07.000
Ben Adams: And then you can optimize it.

102
00:17:07.490 --> 00:17:11.900
Luis Pinto | Besu: What's the benefit of having that

103
00:17:12.480 --> 00:17:17.490
Luis Pinto | Besu: Because if we want to use these new opcodes, and there's no guarantees what is…

104
00:17:17.869 --> 00:17:22.969
Luis Pinto | Besu: What do we gain with that? Can we not just restrict those opcodes to that magic?

105
00:17:23.300 --> 00:17:24.460
Luis Pinto | Besu: But…

106
00:17:26.230 --> 00:17:27.369
Greg: Yeah.

107
00:17:30.160 --> 00:17:32.439
Greg: I'm a little confused here.

108
00:17:32.650 --> 00:17:42.060
Greg: the alternative is is simply to do the check every time you

109
00:17:42.270 --> 00:17:44.839
Greg: Every time you want to run the code.

110
00:17:53.230 --> 00:17:57.389
lightclient: I think he was just asking, like, why allow this backwards compatibility?

111
00:17:58.980 --> 00:18:05.639
Greg: Well, one, just because backwards compelled, it's a good thing to have it.

112
00:18:05.740 --> 00:18:19.429
Greg: If you don't have it, there will be objections that, gee, you know, I wind up needing two interpreters here. One… one for the new code, and one for the old code.

113
00:18:19.430 --> 00:18:31.929
Greg: Not that I can choose to have two interpreters so that I can interpret the new code in a faster way or a different way, but I'm forced to.

114
00:18:31.970 --> 00:18:34.930
Greg: You know, I can't just use a simple interpreter.

115
00:18:35.200 --> 00:18:49.270
Greg: Another reason to have it is the opcodes are useful in their own right. There's useful ways to use them that won't pass that that validation algorithm.

116
00:18:49.440 --> 00:19:07.790
Greg: that can still be traversed in one pass. The EOF validation algorithm was a more complicated algorithm. It required that the code be organized in blocks, that the blocks be in a certain order.

117
00:19:07.830 --> 00:19:15.469
Greg: So… You could… you can do the code in different ways that are still

118
00:19:15.660 --> 00:19:32.460
Greg: you know, still useful. So I don't want to upfront. Just say there's only one way to use these new opcodes when, in fact, there's useful things you can do with them that are not going to pass that validation.

119
00:19:32.830 --> 00:19:42.369
Greg: and the validation isn't fixed for all time. It's…

120
00:19:42.750 --> 00:19:55.849
Greg: The header points to a function on the blockchain and over time different validation can be put in there.

121
00:19:55.900 --> 00:20:12.999
Greg: It can both be less restrictive with fewer constraints. With fewer constraints, with better algorithms, we can prove more. With more constraints, we can prove more.

122
00:20:13.460 --> 00:20:16.450
Greg: That's completely open to the future.

123
00:20:16.720 --> 00:20:18.730
Greg: But…

124
00:20:19.540 --> 00:20:28.649
Greg: As core devs, we long since lost the opportunity to drive this. That was something we could have done 10 years ago.

125
00:20:28.800 --> 00:20:34.569
Greg: But now we have a huge ecosystem, and it's it's gonna be a market, basically.

126
00:20:34.980 --> 00:20:35.870
Greg: Okay.

127
00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:37.760
Greg: Okay.

128
00:20:38.310 --> 00:20:43.609
Greg: And most of the advantage is downstream of the clients.

129
00:20:43.660 --> 00:20:58.960
Greg: It's people who've got the bytecode that need to do things with it. They might need to compile it, they might need to do proofs of correctness, any number of things you can do downstream of the bytecode.

130
00:20:59.470 --> 00:21:00.440
Greg: And…

131
00:21:00.650 --> 00:21:10.199
Greg: Those aren't very visible to the core devs. It's a lot of people. Lots of them are very small shops doing auditing.

132
00:21:10.340 --> 00:21:17.959
Greg: And for the most part they've given up talking to us.

133
00:21:18.580 --> 00:21:26.730
Greg: They've they've got work to do, and fighting with the core devs to get something to change doesn't.

134
00:21:26.900 --> 00:21:29.000
Greg: Doesn't make them any money.

135
00:21:31.470 --> 00:21:40.579
Greg: and the academics. They spend their time writing papers to get just a few percent gain, and how many programs they can analyze.

136
00:21:42.330 --> 00:21:49.030
Greg: So, we're creating a huge amount of technical debt downstream of us. It's mostly invisible.

137
00:21:55.290 --> 00:22:05.250
Greg: For years, I meet people at conferences that just say, please, get rid of dynamic jump. We don't care how, just get rid of it.

138
00:22:05.930 --> 00:22:06.620
Greg: Oh.

139
00:22:14.650 --> 00:22:25.659
Łukasz Rozmej: How useful would that be? Well, this is the first step, definitely, because it's just introducing static jumps, but we won't get reading of dynamic jumps, right? So this is only partially useful.

140
00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:34.409
Greg: Invalidated code. The form is still there, but.

141
00:22:34.770 --> 00:22:40.750
Greg: You know, we insist that… that the jump Address be a constant.

142
00:22:40.860 --> 00:22:52.330
Greg: I don't try to introduce a new kind of jump instruction. EOF tried to do that.

143
00:22:52.820 --> 00:23:02.620
Greg: but then you've gotta figure out how to put the immediates in, you know, without breaking other things.

144
00:23:02.770 --> 00:23:09.149
Greg: there's an eip to do that, but I think it's currently stalled.

145
00:23:09.650 --> 00:23:10.670
Greg: All right.

146
00:23:10.920 --> 00:23:13.650
Greg: Don't want to wait around on that.

147
00:23:15.630 --> 00:23:19.589
Greg: Last time I talked to Martin, he was just going…

148
00:23:19.700 --> 00:23:23.979
Greg: What's the point? Just to to maybe save a bite.

149
00:23:26.480 --> 00:23:28.369
Ben Adams: So we,

150
00:23:31.280 --> 00:23:39.210
Ben Adams: The constraint that the jump and the call sub, et cetera, must be preceded by the push makes it.

151
00:23:39.710 --> 00:23:40.620
Ben Adams: Started.

152
00:23:40.860 --> 00:23:41.500
Ben Adams: Is that correct?

153
00:23:41.500 --> 00:23:43.050
Greg: Right, right.

154
00:23:48.840 --> 00:23:58.849
Luis Pinto | Besu: About the validation phase and the performance, I think Light Client is worried about that. Yeah, I think the disk write for…

155
00:23:58.980 --> 00:24:08.690
Luis Pinto | Besu: The contract creation might actually be, though, the most overhead part of it, and that the validation in itself might not really be

156
00:24:09.010 --> 00:24:14.840
Luis Pinto | Besu: That much overhead, added on top of the contract creation.

157
00:24:15.530 --> 00:24:16.190
Luis Pinto | Besu: So…

158
00:24:16.190 --> 00:24:18.699
Greg: No, it's very fast and easy.

159
00:24:19.260 --> 00:24:26.190
Luis Pinto | Besu: Yeah, for 64 kilobyte contracts. I don't think we're gonna go much higher than that, soon.

160
00:24:27.450 --> 00:24:34.700
Greg: Yeah, it's… it's a one-pass algorithm that doesn't do… Very much work, first step.

161
00:24:35.050 --> 00:24:36.050
Greg: Mmhm.

162
00:24:39.360 --> 00:24:45.179
Luis Pinto | Besu: Regarding the deployed contracts, I guess in the…

163
00:24:45.280 --> 00:25:00.430
Luis Pinto | Besu: most clients, since there's such a performance concern about having them being performant, I think most clients will eventually have their own baked-in validation, which just avoids the EVM interpreter altogether.

164
00:25:00.700 --> 00:25:04.339
Luis Pinto | Besu: I think that that will happen.

165
00:25:05.130 --> 00:25:10.799
Luis Pinto | Besu: So I'm not sure. I feel a bit neutral about having that deployed on-chain.

166
00:25:11.390 --> 00:25:12.220
Greg: Mmhm.

167
00:25:13.710 --> 00:25:15.879
Ben Adams: I mean, we can measure.

168
00:25:16.090 --> 00:25:17.130
Ben Adams: the EVM.

169
00:25:17.290 --> 00:25:18.090
Ben Adams: And.

170
00:25:18.220 --> 00:25:20.520
Ben Adams: the… How long it takes.

171
00:25:25.670 --> 00:25:27.760
Ben Adams: Maybe it's faster.

172
00:25:30.760 --> 00:25:36.189
Greg: It gets done, you know, once at create time.

173
00:25:36.540 --> 00:25:46.400
Greg: and it substitutes for jump test analysis. You don't need to do jump test analysis.

174
00:25:50.070 --> 00:25:59.909
Greg: So I… I just don't… I don't see that it's a big deal, and clients are free to put their own in, for better performance.

175
00:26:00.070 --> 00:26:01.170
Greg: Yum.

176
00:26:02.080 --> 00:26:08.360
Greg: But it makes it possible to write a simple client that's a simple interpreter.

177
00:26:08.570 --> 00:26:12.010
Greg: And pulls.

178
00:26:12.150 --> 00:26:23.720
Greg: Pulls the algorithm off the chain, runs it after the init code, and otherwise… otherwise, it's just a very simple interpreter that you can write right now.

179
00:26:23.950 --> 00:26:24.950
Greg: Yum.

180
00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:31.170
Greg: And.

181
00:26:31.570 --> 00:26:38.309
Greg: The validation is… You know, it's a one-pass algorithm, but it's a bit tricky.

182
00:26:52.920 --> 00:26:55.770
Luis Pinto | Besu: I had a question about call sub.

183
00:26:56.010 --> 00:27:00.610
Luis Pinto | Besu: So, from what I'm understanding, the call sub, can…

184
00:27:00.980 --> 00:27:10.880
Luis Pinto | Besu: see the operand stack before it, right? It's not like the… like in programming languages, when you jump to,

