00:27:11.140 --> 00:27:16.650
Luis Pinto | Besu: A function, you have your own, operand stack.

186
00:27:17.100 --> 00:27:20.369
Luis Pinto | Besu: I don't have access to the ones previously.

187
00:27:20.560 --> 00:27:29.910
Luis Pinto | Besu: Have you given any thought to that? Are there any security concerns about… And that case, or…

188
00:27:30.930 --> 00:27:38.639
Luis Pinto | Besu: I guess we have call… we have call, that does not have previous information about operand stacks.

189
00:27:38.830 --> 00:27:41.150
Luis Pinto | Besu: From previous frames. But, yeah.

190
00:27:42.820 --> 00:27:51.230
Greg: Higher level languages make it look as if it has its own operand stack.

191
00:27:51.810 --> 00:27:52.880
Greg: Oh.

192
00:27:53.260 --> 00:27:57.089
Greg: It may or may not be a separate piece of memory.

193
00:27:57.260 --> 00:28:03.549
Greg: It's not easy to get at anything higher up.

194
00:28:04.130 --> 00:28:09.169
Greg: I'd have to think as to whether it's even possible.

195
00:28:09.520 --> 00:28:14.929
Greg: But… There's an EIP that would make it possible, but it stalled.

196
00:28:18.300 --> 00:28:22.930
Ben Adams: It's… All within the same contract, though, so… You.

197
00:28:24.060 --> 00:28:27.089
Ben Adams: You'd be worrying about the security of the code group.

198
00:28:27.380 --> 00:28:29.320
Ben Adams: I don't see that would be a problem.

199
00:28:31.530 --> 00:28:35.589
Ben Adams: It's not… it's not a call into a different contract.

200
00:28:35.590 --> 00:28:36.180
Luis Pinto | Besu: Yep.

201
00:28:37.900 --> 00:28:42.330
Greg: Yeah, you're just… if you can even do it,

202
00:28:44.790 --> 00:28:50.100
